Stenotus witchelina

can be distinguished from the other Australian 

Stenotus
species

by the following set of characters: yellow coloration without reddish tinge or any brown or black markings (
Figure 1
); vertex distinctly shorter than eye diameter (
Figure 2C
); frons almost flat from lateral view (
Figure 2F, H
); clypeus one-half height of eye anteriorly (
Figure 2D
); labium reaching middle of metasternum (
Figure 2F
); ventral surface of genital capsule 1.7Ã— as long as dorsal surface (
Figure 4J
); right paramere not hooked (
Figure 4G
); right medial endosomal lobe longer than left medial lobe, with field of small spicules, left medial lobe without those small spicules (
Figure 4F
); posterior wall of bursa copulatrix with dorsal lobe (
Figure 6E
). 

Stenotus gressitti

differs from this species in body mostly yellow with reddish tinge (
Figure 1
), vertex as long as eye diameter (
Figure 2B
), frons distinctly bulging (
Figure 2E
), ventral surface of genital capsule 1.3Ã— as long as dorsal surface (
Figure 4E
), right paramere hooked (
Figure 4B
), left medial endosomal lobe longer than right medial lobe and bearing field of small spicules, those spicules absent on right medial endosomal lobe (
Figure 4A
), posterior wall of bursa copulatrix without dorsal lobe (
Figure 6D
). 

Stenotus binotatus

can be separated from 

S. witchelina

by yellow coloration with brown or black markings or stripes (
Figure 1
), vertex as long as eye diameter (as in 
Figure 2B
), clypeus 0.8Ã— height of eye anteriorly, labium reaching abdominal segment VI, right paramere hooked distally (
Figure 5B
), endosoma with fields of small spicules on both medial lobes (
Figure 5A
).

